# WIP Safety Commit — Protect Main

Before making any change that could break existing behaviour **or** introduces a new feature, commit all current work and push it to a **new temporary** checkpoint branch first (do **not** only overwrite the single shared `wip` ref unless the user explicitly asked for that).

**Prerequisite:** When you run the WIP commit flow, follow **`pre-commit-quality-scan.mdc`** first: launch a **new readonly subagent** for a security, quality, and standards scan, then proceed with staging and commit below.

## When to trigger

Run this checkpoint flow before:
- Adding a new endpoint, module, script, or file
- Refactoring or rewriting an existing module
- Changing startup sequences, audio pipeline, or TTS logic
- Modifying `.env` defaults or adding new env vars
- Any change the user describes as "new feature", "add", "integrate", or "rework"
- When the next edit touches a file that is already modified (dirty) in git

## How to do it

```bash
cd "$OPENCLAW_HOME"

# 0 — after readonly subagent scan from pre-commit-quality-scan.mdc (when required)

# 1 — new temp branch (example name; pick a short slug for the work you are about to do)
git checkout -b wip/checkpoint-<short-slug>-20260405

# 2 — stage everything
git add -A

# 3 — commit with a wip message describing what is stable so far
git commit -m "wip: stable checkpoint before <next change>"

# 4 — push the new branch (first push sets upstream)
git push -u origin HEAD

# 5 — optional: return to main (or your previous branch) to do the risky edit there
git checkout main
```

Replace the date segment with the real commit day if needed; if the branch name collides, append `-2`, `-3`, etc.

**Voice:** If Cursor narration is on per **`cursor-agent-narration.mdc`**, after a successful push run **`oc-speak.sh`** once with **priority `1`**: a verbose spoken summary of what was checkpointed, why, and the branch name in speakable form (see **`no-markdown-in-speech.mdc`**). If narration is off, skip speech.

Then make your change on the working tree on your usual branch (e.g. `main`).

## Commit message format

```
wip: stable checkpoint before <what you are about to do>
```

Examples:
- `wip: stable checkpoint before adding SSE event stream`
- `wip: stable checkpoint before refactoring friday-play duration logic`
- `wip: stable checkpoint before new lambdaLaunchProbe init sequence`

## Do NOT do this for

- Typo / comment fixes
- Pure `.env` value changes (no code change)
- Updating this rules file itself

## Announce it

When narration is on: prefer **one** post-push checkpoint explanation (covers outcome and branch name). Optionally precede with a single short pre-commit line only if it adds information the post-push line will not repeat — **max two speak calls** in the checkpoint flow; **`block_until_ms: 0`** always.

Post-push example (adjust the spoken text to match the real branch and message):

```bash
$OPENCLAW_HOME/scripts/oc-speak.sh "Done saving checkpoint. I pushed a new branch wip slash checkpoint slash your slug with everything staged so far, so main stays safe before the next change." 1
```
